1
00:00:30,464 --> 00:00:33,365
<i>[ Radio Chatter,</i>                
<i>  Faint ]</i>                       

2
00:00:35,736 --> 00:00:40,572
[ Siren Wailing In Distance ]   

3
00:00:44,078 --> 00:00:46,779
    [ Sniffs, Clears Throat ]   

4
00:01:10,237 --> 00:01:12,271
                We found a body.

5
00:01:12,273 --> 00:01:15,074
            Her throat was slit 
            from ear to ear.    

6
00:01:15,076 --> 00:01:17,443
    Imagine she bled out        
    pretty quickly after that.  

7
00:01:17,445 --> 00:01:19,578
        But her killer          
        didn't stop there. He-- 

8
00:01:20,548 --> 00:01:23,515
        Well, the pictures      
        speak for themselves.   

9
00:01:26,287 --> 00:01:28,320
        Not very pretty anymore.
        I know.                 

10
00:01:28,322 --> 00:01:30,422
What does any of this           
have to do with me?             

11
00:01:31,325 --> 00:01:33,559
            Something. Nothing. 

12
00:01:34,695 --> 00:01:37,096
        That's what I'm here    
        trying to figure out.   

13
00:01:41,302 --> 00:01:43,435
                You recognize   
                that man?       

14
00:01:44,705 --> 00:01:46,205
            No.                 

15
00:01:46,207 --> 00:01:48,640
            No? Are you sure?   

16
00:01:48,642 --> 00:01:50,509
            Yes.                

17
00:01:50,511 --> 00:01:52,711
        Yes, you're sure,       
        or yes, you recognize   
        the man in the photo?   

18
00:01:54,582 --> 00:01:56,448
    Am I in trouble?            

19
00:01:57,284 --> 00:02:00,452
    Maybe I should, um,         
    have a lawyer?              

20
00:02:02,456 --> 00:02:04,790
        Right now, you and I,   
        we're just having       
        a friendly conversation.

21
00:02:04,792 --> 00:02:06,358
            No one else is here.

22
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:09,528
        You tell me             
        you want an attorney,   
        that's your right.      

23
00:02:09,530 --> 00:02:12,931
        But see, you lawyer up, 
        and, uh, that makes me  
        start to think...       

24
00:02:12,933 --> 00:02:15,167
            that you got        
            something to hide.  

25
00:02:15,169 --> 00:02:17,202
            You got something   
            to hide, Gemma?     

26
00:02:20,741 --> 00:02:22,774
            So I ask again:     

27
00:02:22,776 --> 00:02:25,644
    do you recognize this man?  

28
00:02:31,318 --> 00:02:34,319
    It's Henry.                 
        Dr. Henry Moorehouse.   

29
00:02:35,656 --> 00:02:38,357
        Resident brain          
        over at Baxter Pharm    
        for quite a few years...

30
00:02:38,359 --> 00:02:41,360
            before they had     
            to let him go for-- 

31
00:02:41,362 --> 00:02:44,897
            Well, it looks like 
            "unspecified mental 
             health issues."    

32
00:02:44,899 --> 00:02:46,965
I still don't understand        
what any of this has to--       

33
00:02:46,967 --> 00:02:49,635
                Tell me about   
                your involvement
                with Moorehouse.

34
00:02:49,637 --> 00:02:51,537
            You two were close. 

35
00:02:52,907 --> 00:02:54,540
    That a question?            

36
00:02:54,542 --> 00:02:58,944
                See, along with 
                Miss Sullivan,  

37
00:02:58,946 --> 00:03:02,347
I've got a half a dozen bodies  
laying in the morgue,           

38
00:03:02,349 --> 00:03:07,719
all with similar CODs           
that all somehow keep           
connecting back to Moorehouse.  

39
00:03:07,721 --> 00:03:10,789
    Only, when we finally track 
    the son of a bitch down,    

40
00:03:10,791 --> 00:03:13,225
        someone's already gone  
        and burned the place    
        to the ground.          

41
00:03:13,227 --> 00:03:16,528
    The tech lab was able       
    to salvage a few hard drives
    found in the rubble.        

42
00:03:16,530 --> 00:03:18,497
            But the information 
            on those drives...  

43
00:03:18,499 --> 00:03:20,799
        poses more questions    
        than it does answers.   

44
00:03:25,139 --> 00:03:27,039
                    That's where
                    you come in.

45
00:03:27,041 --> 00:03:29,708
        We already know         
        you worked under him    
        for the last few months.

46
00:03:29,710 --> 00:03:33,512
        I need to know what     
        made Henry Moorehouse   
        murder those people.    

47
00:03:34,215 --> 00:03:36,315
    I'm thirsty.                

48
00:03:36,317 --> 00:03:39,051
                We can get you  
                some water.     

49
00:03:39,053 --> 00:03:42,554
            Now, start          
            from the beginning. 

50
00:03:49,897 --> 00:03:52,898
[ Alarm Beeping ]               

51
00:03:58,038 --> 00:03:59,938
[ Shower Running ]              

52
00:04:23,831 --> 00:04:26,798
[ Ticking ]                     

53
00:04:55,729 --> 00:04:58,764
                    [ Buzzing ] 

54
00:05:47,581 --> 00:05:50,716
<i>[ Man ]</i>                         
<i>You're ready?</i>                   
<i>[ Gemma ] Give me a sec.</i>        

55
00:05:50,718 --> 00:05:52,117
Okay.                           

56
00:05:54,188 --> 00:05:56,555
                [ Sighs ]       

57
00:05:56,557 --> 00:06:00,425
        Hello. I am             
        Dr. Henry Moorehouse.   

58
00:06:00,427 --> 00:06:02,461
    During my tenure            
    at Baxter Pharmaceuticals,  

59
00:06:02,463 --> 00:06:05,931
I was on the brink              
of developing the basis         
for a genetic-level vaccine...  

60
00:06:05,933 --> 00:06:10,402
    that could provide          
    the human body with         
    a type of blanket immunity. 

61
00:06:10,404 --> 00:06:13,739
- What I'm about to show you--  
- So this is what,              
  a cure for cancer?            

62
00:06:15,142 --> 00:06:16,942
                May-Maybe.      
                Think bigger.   

63
00:06:16,944 --> 00:06:19,177
Bigger than cancer?             

64
00:06:19,179 --> 00:06:22,614
                This is a cure  
                for everything. 

65
00:06:22,616 --> 00:06:27,853
        Hepatitis,              
        rabies, influenza,      
        HIV, even cancer.       

66
00:06:27,855 --> 00:06:32,357
        A universal cure        
        that could save millions
        of lives every year.    

67
00:06:32,359 --> 00:06:34,393
How is that even possible?      

68
00:06:34,395 --> 00:06:37,129
            Baxter didn't       
            believe me either.  

69
00:06:37,131 --> 00:06:39,731
            "A waste            
             of time and money,"

70
00:06:39,733 --> 00:06:41,967
            I believe was       
            their exact wording.

71
00:06:41,969 --> 00:06:44,269
Is that why you left?           

72
00:06:44,271 --> 00:06:46,605
            I didn't just leave.

73
00:06:46,607 --> 00:06:50,742
                I took what was 
                rightfully mine.

74
00:06:52,012 --> 00:06:54,446
            Say hello to ELA.   

75
00:06:56,450 --> 00:06:59,151
    [ Gurgling ]                
        I designed her myself.  

76
00:07:01,989 --> 00:07:05,957
    ELA is a living incubator,  
    in vitro and in vivo.       

77
00:07:05,959 --> 00:07:08,527
        She's a breeding ground 
        for a meta-virus...     

78
00:07:08,529 --> 00:07:09,995
            with a unique       
            genetic signature...

79
00:07:09,997 --> 00:07:12,631
        that absorbs, replicates
        and re-codes...         

80
00:07:12,633 --> 00:07:15,634
    any viral load              
    introduced into her system. 

81
00:07:16,870 --> 00:07:20,605
        And from the meta-virus 
        I can engineer          
        a retrovirus.           

82
00:07:20,607 --> 00:07:23,375
                And from that-- 
A universal vaccine.            

83
00:07:23,377 --> 00:07:26,645
        Well, in theory anyway. 

84
00:07:29,149 --> 00:07:30,916
                    [ Sighs ]   
Is it alive?                    

85
00:07:34,888 --> 00:07:39,257
        ELA continues to mature 
        at an astonishing pace. 

86
00:07:39,259 --> 00:07:42,527
    At this rate,               
    we'll be able to begin      
    phase-one serum trials...   

87
00:07:42,529 --> 00:07:45,530
    a full six months ahead     
    of originally anticipated.  

88
00:07:45,532 --> 00:07:50,368
    She's proving to be         
    every bit the miracle       
    I had hoped and planned for.

89
00:07:50,370 --> 00:07:53,605
<i>Gemma-- I fear she</i>              
<i>doesn't quite grasp...</i>          

90
00:07:53,607 --> 00:07:55,707
<i>the importance</i>                  
<i>of what we're doing here...</i>     

91
00:07:55,709 --> 00:07:58,877
    and what Baxter would do    
    if they ever found us out.  

92
00:08:00,848 --> 00:08:05,050
        Still, her presence     
        has been...             
        a welcome addition.     

93
00:08:05,052 --> 00:08:06,751
Remember, kids,                 

94
00:08:06,753 --> 00:08:08,220
don't try this at home.         

95
00:08:11,892 --> 00:08:15,293
[ Henry ]                       
Initiating phase one...         

96
00:08:15,295 --> 00:08:16,895
                        now.    

97
00:08:22,135 --> 00:08:24,102
Here we go.                     
That's it.                      

98
00:08:27,040 --> 00:08:29,407
[ Gemma ]                       
Phosphorene levels              
are stable.                     

99
00:08:29,409 --> 00:08:31,176
Pulse ox normal.                

100
00:08:32,379 --> 00:08:34,946
            Perfect.            
            That's my girl.     

101
00:08:34,948 --> 00:08:37,749
        [ Gurgling ]            
[ Rapid Beeping ]               

102
00:08:37,751 --> 00:08:39,584
[ Beeping Continues ]           

103
00:08:39,586 --> 00:08:42,420
Wait. Wait.                     
Wait. No, that's--              

104
00:08:42,422 --> 00:08:44,356
Oxygen levels                   
are spiking.                    

105
00:08:44,358 --> 00:08:46,291
Shit.                           

106
00:08:46,293 --> 00:08:47,826
Shit.                           
We're red-lining, Henry.        

107
00:08:47,828 --> 00:08:49,794
We're red-lining.               
    No, no, no.                 
    She should be fine.         

108
00:08:49,796 --> 00:08:51,897
The serum                       
should be working.              

109
00:08:53,333 --> 00:08:54,900
    Hang on. Hang on.           

110
00:08:58,805 --> 00:09:01,239
                Give me 20 cc's 
                of atropine.    

111
00:09:01,241 --> 00:09:03,208
            Jesus.              
Where?                          

112
00:09:04,711 --> 00:09:06,611
            It's not working.   

113
00:09:08,549 --> 00:09:10,682
        Henry, it's not working.

114
00:09:10,684 --> 00:09:14,052
[ Rapid Beeping ]               

115
00:09:34,708 --> 00:09:37,609
[ Gemma Gasping ]               

116
00:09:39,079 --> 00:09:40,545
[ Beeping Stops ]               

117
00:09:40,547 --> 00:09:43,315
[ Slow Beeping ]                
                    [ Sighs ]   

118
00:09:58,398 --> 00:09:59,998
[ Sighs ]                       

119
00:10:11,678 --> 00:10:13,244
            [ Clears Throat ]   

120
00:10:13,246 --> 00:10:17,515
        The new cultures have   
        been stacked and packed.

121
00:10:17,517 --> 00:10:19,217
    I'm gonna call it a night.  

122
00:10:21,855 --> 00:10:23,355
                        Doc?    

123
00:10:23,357 --> 00:10:25,290
[ Groaning ]                    

124
00:10:26,026 --> 00:10:28,159
                    [ Laughs ]  
            [ Backpack Drops ]  

125
00:11:50,844 --> 00:11:53,778
[ Gemma ]                       
Ladies and gentlemen,           

126
00:11:53,780 --> 00:11:58,249
I give you                      
the cure for cancer.            

127
00:11:58,251 --> 00:11:59,851
            [ Gurgling ]        

128
00:11:59,853 --> 00:12:02,320
Oh! Fucking gross.              

129
00:12:03,957 --> 00:12:05,724
[ Henry ]                       
Gemma!                          

130
00:12:09,096 --> 00:12:10,862
[ Gemma ]                       
We're rolling.                  

131
00:12:11,765 --> 00:12:13,465
    [ Whispering ]              
    Why didn't you tell me?     

132
00:12:13,467 --> 00:12:15,633
    Today is                    
    a very special day.         

133
00:12:15,635 --> 00:12:17,168
                    [ Gurgling ]

134
00:12:17,170 --> 00:12:19,838
If my calculations              
are correct--                   

135
00:12:19,840 --> 00:12:23,208
and they are--                  

136
00:12:23,210 --> 00:12:27,412
today is going to be            
the turning point               
in man's evolutionary journey.  

137
00:12:27,414 --> 00:12:29,414
                    [ Gurgling ]

138
00:12:31,518 --> 00:12:35,053
[ Gemma ]                       
So much for survival            
of the fittest.                 

139
00:12:35,055 --> 00:12:37,489
    This is survival            
    of the fittest...           

140
00:12:37,491 --> 00:12:41,392
    but on                      
    a cellular level.           

141
00:12:41,394 --> 00:12:45,864
    The, uh,                    
    meta-virus generated        
    within the host body...     

142
00:12:45,866 --> 00:12:50,101
is designed to attack           
weaker cell structures          
and replace them with its own.  

143
00:12:50,103 --> 00:12:52,070
These new cells                 
are hard-coded...               

144
00:12:52,072 --> 00:12:54,873
to be resistant                 
to the introduction             
of outside virus cells...       

145
00:12:54,875 --> 00:12:58,176
or even cancerous cells         
generated within the body.      

146
00:12:58,178 --> 00:12:59,744
So, here we go.                 

147
00:12:59,746 --> 00:13:03,581
First, I'll be extracting       
50 cc's of fluid...             

148
00:13:03,583 --> 00:13:06,050
from one                        
of the lymphatic nodes--        

149
00:13:06,052 --> 00:13:08,820
Henry!                          
        Don't-- Don't touch me! 

150
00:13:10,223 --> 00:13:12,390
            Henry, your hand.   
                Don't touch me. 

151
00:13:12,392 --> 00:13:13,992
                Your hand.      
                    Don't--     

152
00:13:20,667 --> 00:13:23,601
        Henry! Henry?           

153
00:13:23,603 --> 00:13:25,270
                    Henry.      

154
00:13:25,272 --> 00:13:27,539
        [ Muffled, Fading ]     
        Henry, can you hear me? 

155
00:13:27,541 --> 00:13:30,141
        Can you hear me, Henry? 
        Henry.                  

156
00:13:34,781 --> 00:13:36,414
[ Heavy Breathing ]             

157
00:13:36,416 --> 00:13:38,016
                Ready?          

158
00:13:44,157 --> 00:13:45,623
[ Gasps ]                       

159
00:13:45,625 --> 00:13:49,093
[ Heavy Breathing ]             

160
00:13:53,233 --> 00:13:55,333
            What the hell       
            just happened?      

161
00:13:58,839 --> 00:14:01,372
    From...                     

162
00:14:01,374 --> 00:14:02,907
all appearances,                

163
00:14:02,909 --> 00:14:06,211
a spontaneous                   
defense mechanism...            

164
00:14:06,213 --> 00:14:09,214
in response...                  
[ Heavy Breathing ]             

165
00:14:09,216 --> 00:14:11,182
    to a...                     

166
00:14:12,652 --> 00:14:14,285
perceived threat.               

167
00:14:18,191 --> 00:14:19,824
[ Grunts ]                      

168
00:14:19,826 --> 00:14:21,593
Sa-Save those.                  

169
00:14:26,566 --> 00:14:28,933
[ Coughing ]                    

170
00:14:28,935 --> 00:14:31,803
            I thought you said  
            it wasn't sentient. 

171
00:14:31,805 --> 00:14:33,404
It's not. Not--                 

172
00:14:33,406 --> 00:14:36,741
Not in the way that--           
that you and I                  
would perceive it.              

173
00:14:36,743 --> 00:14:38,409
        What if you're wrong?   

174
00:14:40,347 --> 00:14:42,580
How's-- How's that?             

175
00:14:42,582 --> 00:14:47,352
    Well, what if this is       
    a sign from the universe... 

176
00:14:47,354 --> 00:14:52,056
    that... we're not supposed  
    to be fucking around        
    with this kind of thing?    

177
00:14:52,058 --> 00:14:54,225
Language.                       
                    I'm serious.

178
00:14:56,630 --> 00:14:58,529
            We're supposed to   
            get sick...         

179
00:14:59,866 --> 00:15:03,968
                and grow old... 
                and die.        

180
00:15:07,107 --> 00:15:10,408
    What happens when you take  
    that out of the equation?   

181
00:15:12,579 --> 00:15:16,114
You're-- You're underestimating 
what I'm doing here.            

182
00:15:16,116 --> 00:15:18,883
What-What I'm doing is much     
more important than that.       

183
00:15:18,885 --> 00:15:20,218
                    Is it?      

184
00:15:22,622 --> 00:15:24,689
You give it time. You'll see.   

185
00:15:29,062 --> 00:15:30,662
[ Henry ]                       
Recording?                      

186
00:15:35,669 --> 00:15:37,468
                    It's okay.  

187
00:15:37,470 --> 00:15:39,570
            She's dormant now.  

188
00:15:39,572 --> 00:15:42,607
        [ Respirator Wheezing ] 

189
00:16:19,412 --> 00:16:22,447
What's up?                      
We cure cancer yet?             

190
00:16:27,787 --> 00:16:29,554
            Okay.               

191
00:16:30,357 --> 00:16:31,923
Guess not.                      

192
00:16:31,925 --> 00:16:33,891
        I just don't understand 
        why it's not taking.    

193
00:16:33,893 --> 00:16:36,594
        By all accounts,        
        it should be working.   

194
00:16:38,031 --> 00:16:40,565
All right.                      
Well, I'm out.                  

195
00:16:40,567 --> 00:16:43,034
Get some sleep, okay?           

196
00:17:22,142 --> 00:17:24,075
[ Rumbling ]                    

197
00:17:51,905 --> 00:17:54,539
            I wasn't gonna      
            hurt you, you know. 

198
00:17:54,541 --> 00:17:56,674
[ Gurgling ]                    

199
00:17:57,911 --> 00:18:00,144
        Yeah, yeah. I get it.   

200
00:18:01,147 --> 00:18:02,780
Do not touch.                   

201
00:18:02,782 --> 00:18:04,682
                    [ Gurgling ]

202
00:18:04,684 --> 00:18:06,551
    [ Mouthing Words ]          

203
00:18:11,591 --> 00:18:13,091
Excuse me.                      

204
00:18:13,093 --> 00:18:15,193
            [ Marker Rattling ] 

205
00:18:17,130 --> 00:18:19,797
Adding an amino acid string     
to the base...                  

206
00:18:19,799 --> 00:18:24,435
may help prevent                
the meta-virus from             
cannibalizing the host cells.   

207
00:18:24,437 --> 00:18:28,639
The only question               
is how to prevent               
the molecular burnout...        

208
00:18:28,641 --> 00:18:30,875
that occurs--                   
            How about adding    
            a protein receptor? 

209
00:18:30,877 --> 00:18:33,444
It inhibits replication         
of the meta-virus,              
rendering it unusable.          

210
00:18:33,446 --> 00:18:36,881
    - Yes, but if we were to--  
    - Will you please just...   

211
00:18:36,883 --> 00:18:38,749
let me concentrate?             

212
00:18:46,826 --> 00:18:48,459
                            Doc?

213
00:18:48,461 --> 00:18:50,828
            You're gonna want   
            to come see this!   

214
00:18:55,468 --> 00:18:58,436
            So, what are we     
            looking at exactly? 

215
00:19:00,640 --> 00:19:03,007
I'm not entirely sure.          

216
00:19:03,009 --> 00:19:06,878
Although ELA's cell structure   
was designed to mimic our own,  

217
00:19:06,880 --> 00:19:10,882
she has and continues           
to accelerate                   
at an exponential rate.         

218
00:19:12,085 --> 00:19:13,684
            Huh.                

219
00:19:40,146 --> 00:19:41,913
                So?             

220
00:19:41,915 --> 00:19:44,715
            I would be remiss   
            in postulating      
            any theories...     

221
00:19:44,717 --> 00:19:47,518
    until I've had a chance     
    to run some proper tests.   

222
00:19:58,498 --> 00:20:01,232
            [ Clicks ]          
    [ Whirring ]                

223
00:20:01,234 --> 00:20:03,568
                Yeah, that's it.

224
00:20:03,570 --> 00:20:06,571
        With any luck           
        I should, uh, know more 
        in the morning.         

225
00:20:06,573 --> 00:20:07,972
    Perfect!                    

226
00:20:09,842 --> 00:20:11,842
        Let's go.               

227
00:20:13,680 --> 00:20:16,714
                    Go where?   
Food time. I'm starving.        

228
00:20:19,652 --> 00:20:21,419
        Let's go.               

229
00:20:28,228 --> 00:20:30,528
Mmm, mmm!                       

230
00:20:31,531 --> 00:20:34,365
Cherry pie sounds               
pretty good about now.          

231
00:20:36,002 --> 00:20:39,103
Cherry pie,                     
a vanilla Coke...               

232
00:20:39,105 --> 00:20:41,038
and a big                       
cup of coffee.                  

233
00:20:41,040 --> 00:20:42,673
                    For dinner? 

234
00:20:42,675 --> 00:20:44,675
What's the point                
of being grown up...            

235
00:20:44,677 --> 00:20:46,944
if you can't have               
